ol.li:
The line L is spanned by the vector v=\vec{1 1}, and L^\perp is spanned by w={-1 1}. Therefore


                                proj_L (y) = \frac{y \cdot v}{v \cdot v}v  \qquad proj_{L^\perp}(y) = \frac{y \cdot w}{w \cdot w}w


                        We compute


                                proj_L (e_1) = \frac{e_1 \cdot v}{v \cdot v}v = \frac{1}{2}\vec{1 1}
                                \qquad
                                proj_L (e_2) = \frac{e_2 \cdot v}{v \cdot v}v = \frac{1}{2}\vec{1 1}


                                proj_{L^\perp}(e_1) = \frac{e_1 \cdot w}{w \cdot w}w = -\frac{1}{2}\vec{-1 1}
                                \qquad
                                proj_{L^\perp}(e_2) = \frac{e_2 \cdot w}{w \cdot w}w = \frac{1}{2}\vec{-1 1}


                        Therefore, the matrices for proj_L and proj_{L^\perp} are, respectively,


                                \frac{1}{2}\mat{1 1; 1 1} \quad \text{and} \quad \frac{1}{2}\mat{1 -1;-1 1}

statement.p:
Consider the matrix
                A=\mat{1 1 1; 1 1 1; 0 0 0}
                Is A the matrix for the orthogonal projection onto a subspace of \R^3? Why or why not?
